,"en":{"Abt 1063–1090":"about 1063–1090","1063–1090":"1063–1090","1061–1120":"1061–1120","1085–Male":"1085–Deceased","1087–Male":"1087–Deceased","1089–Male":"1089–Deceased","1028–Male":"1028–Deceased","1034–Female":"1034–Deceased","1090":"1090","1087":"1087","1120":"1120","1085":"1085","1063":"1063","1061":"1061","Abt 1087":"about 1087","Abt 1063":"about 1063","Abt 1085":"about 1085","1028":"1028","Abt 1089":"about 1089","1034":"1034","1089":"1089","Bourton, Oxfordshire, England":"Bourton, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom","Of Little Marlow, Buckshire, England":"Little Marlow, Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","Little Marlow, Buckinghamshire, England":"Little Marlow, Buckinghamshire, England","France":"France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Poure","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Fernand, Andre, Fabien, Jean-Pierre, Solange.","French (mainly northern; <b>Poutré</b>): probably derived from Old French <i>poutre</i> ‘young mare, filly’, used as a nickname for a vivacious, vigorous individual.","History: André Poutré <i>dit</i> Lavigne from Valenciennes in Nord, France, married Jeanne Burel in Quebec City, QC, in 1667. His descendants also bear the surname   Lavigne  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Lavigne","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Armand, Jacques, Marcel, Normand, Lucien, Emile, Gilles, Francois, Germain, Michel, Ovila.","French:","from Old French <i>vi(g)ne</i> ‘vineyard’ (from Latin <i>vinea</i>, a derivative of <i>vinum</i> ‘wine’), hence a topographic name for someone who lived near a vineyard or a metonymic occupational name for a vine dresser or the owner of a vineyard (compare   Vigne  ). It is formed with fused feminine definite article <i>la</i>."]}]},{"name":"Adele","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From French  <b>Adèle</b> , an ancient name popular in medieval Europe because of the fame of a 7th-century saint, a daughter of the Frankish king Dagobert II. It is of Germanic origin, from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ (a short form of a two-element name such as <i>Adelheid</i>;  see  Adelaide  ). It was the name of William the Conqueror's youngest daughter (  <i>c.</i>1062–1137 ), who became the wife of Stephen of Blois. However, it died out in England in the later Middle Ages. It was revived in the 19th century, being the name of a character in  Johann Strauss's  opera Die Fledermaus. Its popularity was further reinforced in the 1930s as the name of a character in the novels of  Dornford Yates ."],"variants":[{"name":"Adel","meanings":["From French  <b>Adèle</b> , an ancient name popular in medieval Europe because of the fame of a 7th-century saint, a daughter of the Frankish king Dagobert II. It is of Germanic origin, from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ (a short form of a two-element name such as <i>Adelheid</i>;  see  Adelaide  ). It was the name of William the Conqueror's youngest daughter (  <i>c.</i>1062–1137 ), who became the wife of Stephen of Blois. However, it died out in England in the later Middle Ages. It was revived in the 19th century, being the name of a character in  Johann Strauss's  opera Die Fledermaus. Its popularity was further reinforced in the 1930s as the name of a character in the novels of  Dornford Yates ."]},{"name":"Adelle","meanings":["From French  <b>Adèle</b> , an ancient name popular in medieval Europe because of the fame of a 7th-century saint, a daughter of the Frankish king Dagobert II. It is of Germanic origin, from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ (a short form of a two-element name such as <i>Adelheid</i>;  see  Adelaide  ). It was the name of William the Conqueror's youngest daughter (  <i>c.</i>1062–1137 ), who became the wife of Stephen of Blois. However, it died out in England in the later Middle Ages. It was revived in the 19th century, being the name of a character in  Johann Strauss's  opera Die Fledermaus. Its popularity was further reinforced in the 1930s as the name of a character in the novels of  Dornford Yates ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Adele de Poure was born about 1063, in France, her father, Humphrey le Poure, was 36 and her mother, Ada, was 31. She married Ranulph d'Anvers II. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. She died in 1090, in Bourton, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 28."},"et":{"Abt 1063–1090":"umbes 1063–1090","1063–1090":"1063–1090","1061–1120":"1061–1120","1085–Male":"1085–Surnud","1087–Male":"1087–Surnud","1089–Male":"1089–Surnud","1028–Male":"1028–Surnud","1034–Female":"1034–Surnud","1090":"1090","1087":"1087","1120":"1120","1085":"1085","1063":"1063","1061":"1061","Abt 1087":"umbes 1087","Abt 1063":"umbes 1063","Abt 1085":"umbes 1085","1028":"1028","Abt 1089":"umbes 1089","1034":"1034","1089":"1089","Bourton, Oxfordshire, England":"Bourton, Oxfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Of Little Marlow, Buckshire, England":"Little Marlow, Buckinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Little Marlow, Buckinghamshire, England":"Little Marlow, Buckinghamshire, England","France":"Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"Abt 1063–1090":"noin 1063–1090","1063–1090":"1063–1090","1061–1120":"1061–1120","1085–Male":"1085–Kuollut","1087–Male":"1087